(of uncertain etymology)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Wyleby was born in 1231, in Wilby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of William DeWyleby. He married Mrs. Wyleby in 1274, in Wilby, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. In 1295, his occupation is listed as mayor of dublin in County Dublin, Ireland. He died in 1327, at the age of 96."},"et":{"1231–1327":"1231–1327","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1257–1327":"1257–1327","1199–1259":"1199–1259","1327":"1327","1259":"1259","1257":"1257","from 1295 to 1296":"1295 kuni 1296","1199":"1199","1254":"1254","1231":"1231","1274":"1274","Wilby, Northamptonshire, England":"Wilby, Northamptonshire, England","Dublin, Ireland":"County Dublin, Iirimaa","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1231–1327":"1231–1327","1254–Female":"1254–Kuollut","1257–1327":"1257–1327","1199–1259":"1199–1259","1327":"1327","1259":"1259","1257":"1257","from 1295 to 1296":"vuodesta 1295 vuoteen 1296","1199":"1199","1254":"1254","1231":"1231","1274":"1274","Wilby, Northamptonshire, England":"Wilby, Northamptonshire, England","Dublin, Ireland":"County Dublin, Irlanti","Northamptonshire, England":"Northampto